'''Charles R. Berger''' was an [[United States|American]] [[professor emeritus]] of [[Communication theory|communication]] at the [[University of California, Davis]].<ref name="uc-bio">{{Cite web|title=Charles Berger PhD|url=http://communication.ucdavis.edu/people/fzberger|publisher=University of California, Davis|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Berger died on September 25, 2018, from health complications arising from cancer. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icahdq.org/blogpost/1523657/310331/Charles-R-Berger-1939-2018|title=Charles R. Berger (1939-2018) - International Communication Association|website=www.icahdq.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://communication.ucdavis.edu/news/in-memoriam-professor-emeritus-chuck-berger|title=In Memoriam: Professor Emeritus Chuck Berger — Communication|last=|first=|date=|website=communication.ucdavis.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>

== Education ==

Berger received his [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in [[Psychology]] from [[Pennsylvania State University]]. After completing his undergraduate studies, he attended [[Michigan State University]] where he received his [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] and [[Ph.D.]] in Communication.

== Career ==

He is a Fellow and former president of the [[International Communication Association]]. Berger is best known for his formulation of [[uncertainty reduction theory]].<ref name="uc-bio" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=ICA Fellows|url=http://www.icahdq.org/about_ica/fellows.asp|publisher=International Communication Association|accessdate=25 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213163338/http://www.icahdq.org/about_ica/fellows.asp#|archive-date=2014-12-13|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>

His research interests include message production processes and the processing of threat-related messages by intuitive and rational systems.

He is a former editor of ''[[Human Communication Research]]'' and co-editor (with Sandra Ball Rokeach) of ''Communication Research''. He is a member of several editorial boards of communication journals. He is currently an area editor for the ''International Encyclopedia of Communication''.

He is a Fellow and a Past President of the [[International Communication Association]]. He is a co-recipient (with [[Judee K. Burgoon|Judee Burgoon]]) of NCA’s Mark Knapp Award.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Author - Charles R. Berger, 1994-1999|url=http://www.sagepub.com/authorDetails.nav?contribId=532243|publisher=SAGE Publications|accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>
Berger lives in Davis, California with his wife.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Charles Berger|url=http://www.sagepub.com/authorDetails.nav?contribId=532243}}</ref>

== Publications ==

Berger has published over 100 articles and book chapters. He co-edited the first edition of the [[Handbook of Communication Science]] with Steven H. Chaffee.  He Co-edited the second edition of the Handbook of Communication Science with Michael Roloff and David R. Ewoldsen.

