'''''The Connection''''' is a 2014 documentary<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roston|first1=Tom|title="The Connection" and How Documentaries Can Be Good Medicine (Part 1)|url=https://www.pbs.org/pov/blog/docsoup/2014/10/the-connection-and-how-documentaries-can-be-good-medicine-part-1/#.VSSMiykVdFI|website=PBS.org|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> directed by former ABC journalist Shannon Harvey<ref>{{cite web|title=The Connection|url=http://www.whatsnewinfitness.com.au/the-connection|website=What's New In Fitness|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Colquhoun|first1=James|title=Shannon Harvey (Director Of The Connection Documentary)|url=http://www.foodmatters.tv/author/shannon-harvey-director-of-the-connection-documentary|website=Food Matters|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> which outlines various aspects of mind body medicine,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Collard|first1=Eric|title=Documentary Review: The Connection: Mind Your Body|url=http://www.ecinc.ca/wellness-2/documentary-review-the-connection-mind-your-body/|website=Efficient Coaching Inc|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> such as the role of stress and community. It looks at the effect this has on human health, particularly those with a chronic illness.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Eric|title='The Connection' Explores Potential For Mind-Body Medicine|url=http://54.209.217.48/california/milpitas/-connection-explores-potential-mind-body-medicine|website=Milipatas Patch|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>

It features [[Dean Ornish]], [[Herbert Benson]], [[Jon Kabat-Zinn]], Esther Sternberg, [[Andrew Weil]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pereira|first1=Victoria|title="The Connection" screens at Gallagher|url=http://www.wildcat.arizona.edu/article/2014/09/the-connection-screens-at-gallagher|website=Daily Wildcat|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> Alice Domar, [[David Spiegel]], Craig Hassed, Damien Finniss and Sara Lazar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schulte|first1=Brigid|title=Harvard neuroscientist: Meditation not only reduces stress, here’s how it changes your brain|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/inspired-life/wp/2015/05/26/harvard-neuroscientist-meditation-not-only-reduces-stress-it-literally-changes-your-brain/|website=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> It also features six stories of people who have used mind body medicine while suffering from illnesses including [[multiple sclerosis]], [[infertility]], [[heart disease]], [[cancer]], [[autoimmune disease]] and [[chronic pain]].

